2. Which tool would you choose for business reporting and why?

Power BI wins 80% of enterprise reporting due to:


✅ Microsoft 365 integration (Teams, Excel, SharePoint)
✅ Lower cost ($10 vs $70/user)
✅ Power BI Service (sharing + mobile)
✅ DAX for complex calculations
✅ Automatic refreshes + row-level security

Tableau better for: Creative agencies, advanced geospatial analysis.



3. What is DAX and where is it used?

DAX (Data Analysis Expressions) = Formula language for Power BI + Power Pivot:


Excel: =SUMIFS(A:A, B:B, ">100")
DAX: Total Sales = CALCULATE(SUM(Sales[Amount]), Sales[Region] = "North")

DAX power: Con-aware calculations across related tables:


YTD Growth = 
DIVIDE(
    [Total Sales] - CALCULATE([Total Sales], SAMEPERIODLASTYEAR(Date[Date])),
    CALCULATE([Total Sales], SAMEPERIODLASTYEAR(Date[Date]))
)



4. Why is Tableau preferred for data visualization?

Tableau excels in exploratory analysis and visual storytelling:​


✅ Show Me (auto chart selection)
✅ Advanced visuals (waterfall, bullet, treemap)
✅ Pixel-perfect formatting
✅ Custom territories/heatmaps
✅ Viz in Tooltips (drill-down richness)

Tableau philosophy: "Ask questions of data through visuals first."



5. Explain a real-life scenario where Tableau is better than Power BI.

Scenario: Agency tracks 50 clients × 12 campaigns × daily metrics = Complex visualization needs

Power BI limitations:


❌ Single-page dashboards
❌ Limited chart variety
❌ Manual custom visual imports
❌ Complex layout requirements fail

Tableau wins:

✅ Multi-panel storytelling layouts
✅ Custom color palettes per client
✅ Interactive treemaps (campaign hierarchy)
✅ Geospatial client territories
✅ Motion charts (campaign lifecycle)
✅ Viz-in-tooltip (daily metrics drill)

Client deliverable: Tableau dashboard → Executive wows → 30% contract renewal boost.
